{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox television | show_name = Fake or Fortune? | image = FakeorFortuneTitleCard.jpg | caption = | genre = Documentary | creator = | writer = | director = | creative_director = | presenter = {{Unbulleted list|[[Fiona Bruce]]|[[Philip Mould]]}} | theme_music_composer = | opentheme = | endtheme = | composer = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | num_episodes = 22 | list_episodes = | executive_producer = | producer = Simon Shaw | editor = | cinematography = | camera = | runtime = 60 minutes | company = | distributor = | network = [[BBC One]] | picture_format = | audio_format = | first_run = | first_aired = {{Start date|2011|06|19|df=y}} | last_aired = present | website = | website_title = | num_series = 7 }} '''''Fake or Fortune?''''' is a [[BBC One]] television series which examines the [[provenance]] and attribution of notable [[art]]works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rts.org.uk/award/rts-west-england-awards-2016|title=RTS West of England Awards 2016 {{!}} Royal Television Society|website=rts.org.uk|language=en|access-date=23 February 2017}}</ref> Since the first series aired in 2011, ''Fake or Fortune?'' has drawn audiences of 5 million viewers in the UK<ref name="times">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/its-a-copy-fake-or-fortune-stars-try-to-halt-rival-show-6gstpwtrz |title=It’s a copy: Fake or Fortune? stars try to halt rival show |last=Brooks |first=Richard |date=4 December 2016 |work=The Times |access-date=26 August 2017}}</ref>, the highest for an arts show in that country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbcstudios.com/case-studies/fake-or-fortune|title=Fake or Fortune|website=www.bbcstudios.com|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>
''Fake or Fortune?'' was created by [[art dealer]] and [[art history|art historian]] [[Philip Mould]] and producer Simon Shaw, inspired by Mould’s book ''Sleuth'' (2009), which was the programme’s working title during the development phase.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/print-edition/2017/august/2304/interview/behind-the-scenes-at-fake-or-fortune/|title=Behind the scenes at Fake or Fortune? {{!}} Antiques Trade Gazette|last=Media|first=ATG|website=www.antiquestradegazette.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-12}}{{subscription required}}</ref> It is co-presented by Mould and [[journalism|journalist]] [[Fiona Bruce]], with specialist research carried out by Dr. [[Bendor Grosvenor]] during the first five seasons. Forensic analysis and archival research is carried out by various fine art specialists.<ref name="FoF">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0125by8|title=Fake or Fortune?|publisher=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://courtauld.ac.uk/courtauld-advises-bbc-fake-or-fortune|title=Courtauld advises BBC Fake or Fortune|date=28 July 2015|newspaper=The Courtauld Institute of Art|access-date=23 February 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Each series first aired on BBC One, except the third series accidentally first aired on [[Sveriges Television|SVT]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arthistorynews.com/articles/2575_Trailer_for_Fake_or_Fortune_series_3|title=Trailer for 'Fake or Fortune?' series 3 - Art History News - Bendor Grosvenor|website=Arthistorynews.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> The seventh series aired in August and September 2018.
==Synopsis== In each episode Philip Mould and Fiona Bruce focus their attention on a painting (or a group of paintings), usually related to one particular artist. Season 7, episode 5 saw the show tackle their first [[sculpture]], a work attributed to [[Alberto Giacometti]]. The team, assisted by [[Bendor Grosvenor]] in series 1 to 5, investigate the paintings on a number of fronts: establishing the provenance of the piece by working backwards from present day to the time of the work's creation; on a forensic level, with investigation and scientific tests on the materials used to help establish specific time frames; and examining the unique painting styles and quirks of the artist. This evidence is then presented to established authorities to help demonstrate the legitimacy of the work and its possible addition to the relevant [[catalogue raisonné]].
