==Episodes== {{cleanup section|reason=summaries vary widely in length and quality, see talk|date=September 2018}} ===Series 1 (2011)=== There were four episodes in the first series, which started on 19 June 2011:
{{Episode table |background=#FA8072 |overall= |series= |title= |aux1= |airdate= |country=UK |aux1T= Produced and directed by |episodes= {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 1 | EpisodeNumber2 = 1 | Title = Monet | DirectedBy = Nicky Illis | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|6|19|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = The authenticity of the [[Claude Monet|Monet]] painting ''[[Bords de la Seine à Argenteuil]]''.<ref name="FoF1">{{Cite episode| title = Monet | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0125bz7 | accessdate = 4 August 2011 | series = Fake or Fortune? | network = [[BBC]] | station = | airdate = 19 June 2011 | seriesno = 1 | number = 1}}</ref><ref name="Radford">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8581959/Fake-or-Fortune-BBC-One-review.html|title=''Fake or Fortune?'' BBC One, review|last=Radford|first=Ceri|date=19 June 2011|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The [[Wildenstein Institute]], presented with considerable evidence of the painting's authenticity, controversially rejected it as a Monet and was criticised by Philip Mould.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartsdesk.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=3936:fake-or-fortune?-episodes-1-2-bbc1&Itemid=27 |title=Reviews |publisher=The Arts Desk |date=23 March 2012 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> (The owner subsequently sued the Institute, but lost.<ref name="Grosvenor">{{cite web|url=http://www.arthistorynews.com/articles/2777_Fake_or_Fortune_Monet_owner_loses_Paris_court_case|title='Fake or Fortune?' Monet owner loses Paris court case |last=Grosvenor |first=Bendor |authorlink=Bendor Grosvenor |work=Art History News |accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>) | LineColor = FA8072 }} {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 2 | EpisodeNumber2 = 2 | Title = Homer | DirectedBy = Nicola Lafferty | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|6|26|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = The ownership of the painting ''[[Children Under a Palm]]'' by [[Winslow Homer]].<ref name="FoF2">{{Cite episode | title = Homer | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0125gq3 | accessdate = 4 August 2011 | series = Fake or Fortune? | network = [[BBC]] | airdate = 26 June 2011 | seriesno = 1 | number = 2}}</ref> | LineColor = FA8072 }} {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 3 | EpisodeNumber2 = 3 | Title = Van Meegeren | DirectedBy = Nicky Illis | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|7|3|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = The authenticity of the painting ''[[The Procuress (Dirck van Baburen)|The Procuress]]'', owned by the [[Courtauld Institute]]. It was determined to be a forgery committed by [[Han van Meegeren]].<ref name="FoF3">{{Cite episode | title = Van Meegeren | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b012fvfh | accessdate = 4 August 2011 | series = Fake or Fortune? | network = [[BBC]] | airdate = 3 July 2011 | seriesno = 1 | number = 3}}</ref> | LineColor = FA8072 }} {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 4 | EpisodeNumber2 = 4 | Title = Rembrandt | DirectedBy = Ben Southwell | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|7|10|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = ''Man in an Oriental Costume'', once attributed to [[Rembrandt]] as a portrait of the artist's father, was on sale in a gallery in Cape Town, South Africa. The painting was identified as a work [[Nazi plunder|looted by the Nazis]] and was reattributed to [[Isaac de Jouderville]].<ref name="FoF4">{{Cite episode | title = Rembrandt | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b012m6p5 | accessdate = 4 August 2011 | series = Fake or Fortune? | network = [[BBC]] | airdate = 10 July 2011 | seriesno = 1 | number = 4}}</ref> | LineColor = FA8072 }} }} <gallery caption="Works featured in series 1" mode="packed"> File:Bords de la Seine a Argenteuil - Monet.jpg|''{{Lang|fr|Bords de la Seine à Argenteuil}}'' File:Winslow Homer's 'Children Under a Palm Tree'.jpg|''Children Under a Palm Tree'' File:The Procuress.jpg|''The Procuress'' File:Man in an Oriental Costume - Isaac de Jouderville.jpg|''Man in an Oriental Costume'' </gallery>
===Series 2 (2012)=== The first episode of the second series was shown in the UK on 16 September 2012. The series had three episodes:
{{Episode table |background=#006600 |overall= |series= |title= |aux1= |airdate= |country=UK |aux1T= Produced and directed by |episodes= {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 5 | EpisodeNumber2 = 1 | Title = Degas and the Little Dancer | DirectedBy = Robert Murphy | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|9|16|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = ''Danseuse Bleue et Contrebasses'', with an apparent signature by [[Edgar Degas]]. It had been bought as a Degas in 1948 with an outline provenance going back to the artist's studio. Scientific analysis of the paint confirmed that it was consistent with the 1890s. Research confirmed the provenance, and the painting was accepted as an authentic Degas and added to the ''{{lang|fr|catalogue raisonne}}''.<ref>{{Cite episode | title = Degas and the Little Dancer | series = Fake or Fortune? | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01mxxzg | accessdate = 19 September 2012 | network = BBC | date = 16 September 2012 | seriesno = 2 | number = 1 }}</ref> | LineColor = 006600 }} {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 6 | EpisodeNumber2 = 2 | Title = Turner: A Miscarriage of Justice? | DirectedBy = Nicky Illis<ref name="RadioTimes22">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/r89jy/fake-or-fortune--series-2---2-turner-a-miscarriage-of-justice |title=Archived copy |accessdate=23 February 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226122859/http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/r89jy/fake-or-fortune--series-2---2-turner-a-miscarriage-of-justice |archivedate=26 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }} </ref> | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|9|23|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = Three paintings attributed to [[J. M. W. Turner]], ''[[The Beacon Light]]'', ''Off Margate'' and ''Margate Jetty'', in the collection of the [[National Museum of Wales]].<ref>{{Cite episode | title = Turner: A Miscarriage of Justice? | series = Fake or Fortune? | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01n39kg | accessdate = 19 September 2012 | network = BBC | date = 23 September 2012 | seriesno = 2 | number = 2}}</ref> These had been donated by two sisters: [[Gwendoline Davies|Gwendoline]] and [[Margaret Davies]]. In the 1950s, they had been judged to be fake, but as a result of the programme's research, they are now accepted as genuine. | LineColor = 006600 }} {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 7 | EpisodeNumber2 = 3 | Title = Van Dyck: What Lies Beneath | DirectedBy = Rachel Jardine | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|9|30|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = ''A [[portrait of Queen Henrietta Maria, as St Catherine]]'' attributed to [[Anthony van Dyck]], belonging to Mould.<ref>{{Cite episode | title = Van Dyck: What Lies Beneath | series = Fake or Fortune? | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01n62dw | accessdate = 5 October 2012 | network = BBC | date = 30 September 2012 | seriesno = 2 | number = 3}}</ref><ref name="Wilson">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9544456/Van-Dyck-or-Van-Dupe.html|title=Van Dyck or Van Dupe?|last=Wilson|first=Benji|date=16 September 2012|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=19 September 2012}}</ref> This was shown to be an incomplete portrait of Queen [[Henrietta Maria]] (wife of Charles I) which had later been enlarged and painted over. | LineColor = 006600 }} }} <gallery caption="Selected works featured in series 2" mode="packed"> File:J.M.W. Turner - The Beacon Light.jpg|Turner – ''The Beacon Light'' File:J.M.W. Turner - Off Margate.jpg|Turner – ''Off Margate'' File:J.M.W. Turner - Margate Jetty.jpg|Turner – ''Margate Jetty'' File:Van Dyke Henrietta before.jpg|Van Dyck – ''Portrait of Queen Henrietta Maria, as St Catherine'' before restoration </gallery>
===Series 3 (2014)=== The third series features four episodes. The first episode was first shown on 27 December 2013, on Sweden's SVT, with episodes 2 and 3 shown in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/konstdeckarna/se-program/del-1-1506|title=Del 1 av 3 - SVT.se|date=30 December 2013|website=Svt.se|accessdate=21 August 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234742/http://www.svt.se/konstdeckarna/se-program/del-1-1506|archivedate=30 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Philip Mould described the appearance on Swedish television weeks ahead of the British premiere as a "weird BBC World cock-up".<ref name="Tweet-418435891338964992">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/philipmould/status/419265673916088320|title=A weird BBC world cock up but I'm delighted for Sweden. As we've not finished the 4th prog - stranger still.|last=Mould|first=Philip|date=4 January 2014|website=Twitter |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> SVT on its website described the programme at the time as a "{{lang|sv|Brittisk dokumentärserie från 2012}}" (British documentary from 2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/konstdeckarna/nya-mysterier-for-experterna|title=Nya mysterier för experterna i tredje säsongen|website=Svt.se|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>
{{Episode table |background=#005999 |overall= |series= |title= |aux1= |airdate= |country=UK |aux1T= Produced and directed by |episodes= {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 8 | EpisodeNumber2 = 1 | Title = Édouard Vuillard | DirectedBy = Nicky Illis<ref name="RadioTimes31">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/crtdcw/fake-or-fortune--series-3---1-vuillard|title=Series 3, Episode 1 listing |publisher=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|01|19|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = One of a [[The Grand Teddy tea-rooms paintings|group of paintings]] reputedly by French post-impressionist [[Édouard Vuillard]], purchased speculatively by a writer, Keith Tutt. The investigation unearths documentation proving the painting is genuine and worth approximately £250,000.<ref name="Huff vuillard">{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Painting Bought For £3,000 On Ebay Actually Worth A Fortune |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/01/20/ebay-painting-fortune_n_4630252.html |accessdate=24 January 2014|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=20 January 2014 }}</ref> The Wildenstein Institute panel unanimously accepted Tutt's painting as Vuillard's work. The programme also shows that the painting is part of a pair, the other having been sold by the previous owner on eBay.<ref name="Huff vuillard" />
| LineColor = 005999 }}
{{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 9 | EpisodeNumber2 = 2 | Title = John Constable | DirectedBy = Robert Murphy<ref name="RadioTimes32">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/cryptm/fake-or-fortune--series-3---2-constable|title=Series 3, Episode 2 listing |publisher=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|01|26|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = Two different paintings attributed to [[John Constable]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c21media.net/screenings/all3mediainternational/fake-or-fortune-series-3|title=Fake or Fortune series 3|website=C21media|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> one of Yarmouth Jetty and the other called ''A Sea Beach Brighton''. The former turns out to be "most likely" by Constable, but heavily overpainted by another hand; the latter, formerly in the [[Boston Museum of Fine Arts]] until sold in the 1990s, is deemed a genuine Constable.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.svtplay.se/video/1701145/del-2-av-3 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001220/http://www.svtplay.se/video/1701145/del-2-av-3 |archivedate=31 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }} </ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title= John Constable |episodelink= |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b03srsjl/Fake_or_Fortune_Series_3_Constable/ |accessdate= 26 January 2014 |series= Fake or Fortune |network= BBC |date= 26 January 2014 |seriesno= 3 |number= 2 |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> | LineColor = 005999 }} {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 10 | EpisodeNumber2 = 3 | Title = Marc Chagall | DirectedBy = Robert Murphy<ref name="RadioTimes33">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/csh8rr/fake-or-fortune--series-3---3-chagall|title=Series 3, Episode 3 listing |publisher=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|02|02|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = ''Nude, 1909-10'' was bought by a Leeds property developer in the belief that it was a genuine but unauthenticated work by [[Marc Chagall]]. Forensic tests showed that it was painted with pigments not available at the time it was purported to have been painted. It was submitted to the "Chagall Committee", who ruled that it was a fake and ordered its destruction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/feb/01/chagall-could-be-furnt-fortune-or-fake|title=The man whose 'real Chagall' could now be burnt as a fake|first=Dalya|last=Alberge|date=1 February 2014|accessdate=21 August 2017|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>
