===Series 6 (2017)===
The sixth series started on 20 August 2017.<ref name="S6E1">{{Cite episode |title=Constable |series=Fake or Fortune? |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b092sh3q |accessdate=20 August 2017 |network= [[BBC Television]] |date=20 August 2017 |seriesno=6 |number=1 |transcript= |transcripturl= }}</ref> It was originally planned to have four episodes before one was postponed.<ref name="Giacometti">{{cite tweet|user=philipmould|number=906992186687983616|date=10 September 2017 |author= Philip Mould|title= Apology accepted. Next week's #fakeorfortune(Giacometti) is postponed pending further investigations.TX date to be announced. Repeat instead}}</ref>
{{Episode table |background=#ffe100|overall= |series= |title= |aux1= |airdate= |country=UK |aux1T= Produced and directed by |episodes= {{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 20 | EpisodeNumber2 = 1 | Title = Constable | DirectedBy = Nicky Illis | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|08|20|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = A painting, previously bought and sold, twice, by Philip Mould is shown to be by [[John Constable]]. Mould's previous attempts to prove this had failed to convince experts. Its provenance, from the current owner all the way back to Constable's estate, via whisky distiller [[John Dewar, 2nd Baron Forteviot|John Dewar]] and soap manufacturer [[Thomas J. Barratt]], is established. Stylistic details, verified by Constable experts Annie Lyles and Sarah Cove, date the painting to the correct period. Mould, who sold the painting for £35,000 in 2000, is sanguine about losing out on its estimated £2million value.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fake or Fortune art expert confronted with £2m Constable masterpiece he sold for just £35,000|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/20/fake-2-million-fortune-presenter-philip-mould-let-slip-undiscovered/|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 August 2017|date=20 August 2017}}</ref> | LineColor = ffe100 }}
{{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 21 | EpisodeNumber2 = 2 | Title = Tom Roberts | DirectedBy = Francis Welch | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|09|03|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = [[Queensland]] residents Joe and Rosanna Natoli bought a painting with the signature "[[Tom Roberts]]" at auction for £7,500. Expert opinion after the purchase, however, was that it was not by the important Australian impressionist of that name. [[Infrared]] examination revealed that the back had the title "Rejected", the name Tom Roberts and an address in London's [[Haymarket, London|Haymarket]] that was shown to be Roberts' address while studying at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]]. Roberts' sketchbooks showed initial studies which appeared to be preliminaries for the work under investigation. One of the leading authorities on Roberts' work, Mary Eagle of the [[State Library of New South Wales]], accepts it as genuine and Mould values it in excess of £200,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2017/sep/04/fake-tom-roberts-painting-lost-for-136-years-revealed-to-be-worth-325000|title=Lost for 136 years: ‘fake’ Tom Roberts painting bought for £7,500 could sell for $1m|first=Susan|last=Chenery|date=3 September 2017|publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref> | LineColor = ffe100 }}
{{Episode list | EpisodeNumber = 22 | EpisodeNumber2 = 3 | Title = Paul Gauguin | DirectedBy = Rachel Jardine | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|09|10|df=yes}} | ShortSummary = The team investigate two possible works by [[Paul Gauguin]] which have been brought to their attention. One appeared to be the first pencil sketch for Gauguin's Tahitian masterpiece ''[[When Will You Marry?|When Will you Marry?]].'' It had been bought by the viewer's art historian grandfather, but its authenticity was in doubt because it appeared to be a copy of a sketch in Gauguin's notebook. The team establish provenance that takes it back to Gauguin and show that it had been cut from the sketchbook sometime between 1916 and 1932. It is accepted as genuine by the Wildenstein Institute.
The second possible Gauguin is a still life depicting a bowl of fruit which had been sold as a genuine Gauguin several times and had appeared in a [[catalogue Raisonne]]. However, the signature and dedication had been added after the original paint had dried and the signature did not appear genuine. The sale in which it had first appeared included a number of works now attributed to other artists. Connoisseurship also raises doubts about the style and Mould and Bruce conclude that it is not genuine. | LineColor = ffe100 }}
}}
