{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Leo the Great and Attila by Raffael.png | title=The Meeting of Leo the Great and Attila | image_size=300px | artist=[[Raphael]] | year=1514 | type=[[Fresco]] | height_metric=500 | width_metric=750 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Vatican City]] | museum =[[Apostolic Palace]] }}
'''''The Meeting of Leo I and Attila''''' is a [[fresco]] by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Renaissance]] artist [[Raphael]] and his assistant [[Giulio Romano]]. It was painted in 1514 as part of Raphael's commission to decorate the rooms that are now known as the ''[[Raphael Rooms|Stanze di Raffaello]]'', in the [[Apostolic Palace]] in the [[Vatican City|Vatican]]. It is located in the ''Stanza di Eliodoro'', which is named after ''[[The Expulsion of Heliodorus from the Temple]]''.
The painting depicts the meeting between the [[Pope Leo I]] and [[Attila|Attila the Hun]], and includes the images of [[Saint Peter]] and [[Paul of Tarsus|Saint Paul]] in the sky bearing swords. Initially, Raphael depicted Leo I with the face of [[Pope Julius II]] but after Julius' death, [[Raphael]] changed the painting to resemble the new [[pope]], [[Pope Leo X|Leo X]].
==External links== *[http://cdm16028.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/107497 ''The Vatican: spirit and art of Christian Rome''], a book from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries (fully available online as PDF), which contains material on this work
